4,"location_city":"Milford","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","officiant":"Major Robert Treat, Deputy Governor of Connecticut"}],"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 14"},{"short":"Caroline Gaylord Newton 1914"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"is_placeholder":false,"former_ids":[],"baptism":{"year":1656,"month":6,"day":6,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"Married by Connecticut's future governor in 1680","body":"His marriage to Lydia Ford on April 14, 1680 in Milford was performed by Major Robert Treat, then Deputy Governor of Connecticut. Treat would become Governor in 1683 and remain in office until 1698 — the same year John Newton died."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Built his house next to his father's","body":"He built his house immediately adjacent to Roger Newton Sr.'s on the same Milford home lot. His daughter Prudence — eighteen months old — was 'just old enough to run across the yard to her grandfather's' during Roger's final illness in early 1683."},{"number":3,"category":"death","header":"May 1699 deposition: widow Lydia and four children","body":"He died in May 1699 in Milford. Lydia's deposition for the May 18 estate inventory survives, listing their children — Prudence about 18, Thomas about 17, Ezekiel, and John about 2. She was 38 and a widow with four to raise."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Lydia Ford lived 48 years a widow","body":"Lydia Ford remained a widow until her death in 1747 at age 86 — 48 years after John's death. Milford Land Records show numerous transactions in her name, and her 1746 will divided the estate among her surviving children and grandchildren."}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"artworks":[],"bio":{"display_name":"John Newton","first_name":"John","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"documents":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"john-newton-1656"},"I00012":{"id":"I00012","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"is_progenitor":false},"birth":{"year":1661,"month":3,"day":15,"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1747,"month":10,"day":23,"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM005"},"parents":{"father_id":"X00012","mother_id":"X00013"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00014","children_ids":["H00055","H00042","H00057","H00059","X00012"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1699,"date_year":1680,"date_month":4,"date_day":14}],"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 14"},{"short":"Ford Genealogy 1916","full":"Eliakim Reed Ford, Ford Genealogy (Oneonta, N.Y.: E.R. Ford, 1916), p. 15"},{"short":"Jacobus 1976","full":"Donald Lines Jacobus, History and Genealogy of the Families of Old Fairfield (Baltimore: Genealogical Publishing Co., 1976), p. 368"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"is_placeholder":false,"former_ids":[],"baptism":{},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Widowed at 37 — outlived John by 48 years","body":"John Newton died in May 1699, leaving Lydia with five children — the youngest barely two years old. She lived as a widow in Milford until October 23, 1747, dying at roughly age eighty-five after forty-eight years on her own."}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"artworks":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Lydia Ford Newton","first_name":"Lydia","last_name":"Newton","married_names":["Newton"],"maiden_name":"Ford"},"documents":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"lydia-ford-1661"},"I00003":{"id":"I00003","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"is_progenitor":false},"birth":{"year":1620,"month":1,"day":1,"country":"England","date_precision":"approximate"},"death":{"year":1683,"month":6,"day":7,"city":"Milford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","date_precision":"exact"},"parents":{"father_research_notes":"Said to be of the family of Sir Isaac Newton; possibly son of a Samuel Newton. Parentage unproven — see research_notes."},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00003","children_ids":["H00011","H00012","H00013","H00014","H00015","H00016","H00017","H00018"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1676,"date_year":1644,"location_country":"United States"}],"tags":["minister","farmington_founder","seven_pillars","yale_connection","missionary","great_migration","indigenous_rights","yale_founder"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry g-45"},{"short":"Flagg 1926","page":"pp. 255-256"},{"short":"Caroline Gaylord Newton 1914","full":"Caroline Gaylord Newton, Rev. Roger Newton, Deceased 1683, and One Line of his Descendants (Durham, Conn., 1914), pp. 3-10"},{"short":"Leonard 1915","full":"Ermina Newton Leonard, Newton Genealogy (Salem, Mass: Higginson Book Company, 1915), p. 700"},{"short":"Hulburt 1967","full":"Mabel S. Hulburt, Farmington Church and Town (Stonington, Conn: The Pequot Press, 1967), p. 8"},{"short":"Cutter 1913","full":"William Richard Cutter, New England Families, Genealogical and Memorial (New York: Lewis Historical Publishing, 1913), vol. 3, p. 1730"},{"short":"N.E. Reg.","volume":"11","page":"323"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["religion","education"],"notable_blurb":"Founding Farmington pastor; trained Yale's first rector","primary_url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/newton-roger-1683","primary_url_label":"Native Northeast Portal biography"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"religion","header":"Hooker trained him; he founded Farmington's church","body":"Roger Newton studied theology at Hartford under Thomas Hooker and, around 1645, married Hooker's eldest daughter, Mary. Ordained the first pastor of Farmington in 1652, he later served twenty-three years as the second pastor of Milford."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"He trained Yale's first rector at his table","body":"As Hooker had trained him, Newton took young men into his Milford home for theological study. One was Abraham Pierson Jr., who became the first rector of Yale College."},{"number":3,"category":"religion","header":"He sheltered the fugitive regicides near Milford","body":"From 1661 the regicide judges Edward Whalley and William Goffe — hunted for signing the death warrant of Charles I — hid in a cellar near Newton in Milford. Their presence was kept secret through the two years they remained."},{"number":4,"category":"social_reform","header":"He brought Tunxis members into the church","body":"Newton did missionary work among the Tunxis and witnessed the 1650 agreement between Connecticut and the tribe. A few Tunxis became members of his Farmington church, with the standing that membership carried."},{"number":5,"category":"character","header":"He left Farmington in a year of calamity","body":"Newton departed Farmington in 1657 after a season of disaster — a man named Scott was murdered, and the house of John Hart burned with most of the family inside. He waited months in Boston for passage to England before settling instead at Milford."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"X00094","display_label":"was received into Milford Church by Newton, 1661","link_text":"Miles Merwin"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00067","display_label":"also sheltered the regicides, at Guilford","link_text":"Gov. William Leete"},{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"X02127","display_label":"trained by Newton; became Yale's first rector","link_text":"Rev. Abraham Pierson Jr."},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"H00007","display_label":"succeeded Newton as Farmington's pastor","link_text":"Rev. Samuel Hooker"}],"quotes":[],"is_placeholder":false,"baptism":{},"residence":{"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"education":[{"dates":"Easter 1636","type":"matriculation","school_name":"King's College, Cambridge"},{"institution_id":"INST002","notes":"Studied at Harvard but name not on graduate list. Some early Harvard records in which his name would naturally appear were accidentally burned; uncertain he received a diploma. Cotton Mather nevertheless speaks of him as one of the young students who came from England to finish their education in America."}],"bio":{"title":"Reverend","display_name":"Rev. Roger Newton Sr.","first_name":"Roger","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[],"suffix":"Sr.","bio_blurb":"First pastor of Farmington; second of Milford","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781475281/rogernewtonsr_mspjci.png"},"documents":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002","relationship":"alumnus"}],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"career":[{"role":"Pastor (founding)","organization":"First Church of Farmington","location":"Farmington, Connecticut","start_year":1652,"end_year":1657,"notes":"Ordained the church's first pastor, October 13, 1652."},{"role":"Pastor","organization":"First Church of Milford","location":"Milford, Connecticut","start_year":1660,"end_year":1683,"notes":"Second pastor; installed August 22, 1660."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM005","plot_notes":"Buried in Founders' Cemetery (Rev. Peter Prudden's Garden) on the Wepawaug; 1889 memorial at Founders Memorial Bridge, Milford."},"slug":"roger-newton-sr-1620"},"H00003":{"id":"H00003","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":2,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"is_progenitor":false},"birth":{"year":1623,"month":1,"day":1,"country":"England"},"death":{"year":1676,"month":2,"day":4,"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM005","plot_notes":"Buried in Peter Prudden's Garden — no tombstone remains"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00001","mother_id":"I00001"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00003","children_ids":["H00011","H00012","H00013","H00014","H00015","H00016","H00017","H00018"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death","end_year":1676,"date_year":1644,"location_country":"United States"}],"tags":["great_migration"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry g-46"},{"short":"Flagg 1926","page":"pp. 256-257"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"is_placeholder":false,"baptism":{},"residence":{"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"cousin_marriage","related_id":"H00024","display_label":"Her daughter Sarah Newton married her first cousin John Wilson.","link_text":"John Wilson"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Cared for her mother on the Hartford migration","body":"According to the Newton family genealogy, Mary was the daughter responsible for caring for her mother Susanna on the arduous journey from Cambridge to Hartford in 1636 — a journey in which Mrs. Hooker 'was carried on a horse litter' in poor health. Mary was roughly 13 years old."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Stayed in Hartford while Newton built Farmington","body":"When Roger Newton went to establish the church at Farmington in the late 1640s, Mary remained in Hartford — their son Samuel's baptism on October 20, 1646 appears on the Hartford register, placing her there while her husband laid the groundwork for the congregation he would formally organize."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Eight children born across three Connecticut towns","body":"The family's migrations are recorded in their children's birthplaces: Samuel and Roger Jr. born in Hartford; Susannah and John in Farmington; Ezekiel back in Hartford; then Sarah, Mary, and Alice in Milford — where the family finally settled and where Mary died on February 4, 1676."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Probably born in Esher near Hooker's curacy","body":"Newton family genealogy says she was born around 1623, probably at Esher, Surrey — where Thomas Hooker had served as curate from c. 1618 to 1625. Esher was also where Hooker met her mother Susanna Garbrand."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Hooker Newton","first_name":"Mary","last_name":"Newton","married_names":["Newton"],"maiden_name":"Hooker"},"documents":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"mary-newton-1623"},"X00012":{"id":"X00012","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1624},"d